"""AP ELA: 2 units matching curriculum (AP Lang, AP Lit)"""

AP_ELA = [
  # Unit 1 — AP English Language and Composition
  [
    {"title":"Rhetorical Situation and Claims","problems":[
      {"q":"What are the five elements of the rhetorical situation (SOAPS)?","ex":"Speaker, Occasion, Audience, Purpose, Subject.","a":"Speaker: who is communicating, their background and credibility. Occasion: the context and moment that prompted the text. Audience: the intended recipients and their characteristics. Purpose: what the writer wants to achieve (inform, persuade, entertain, call to action). Subject: the topic being addressed. Analyzing SOAPS helps explain every choice the writer makes.","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"What is the difference between a thesis and a claim? What makes a claim arguable?","ex":"Think about what can be debated.","a":"A thesis is the central argument of an essay. A claim is any arguable statement that requires evidence and reasoning to support. A claim is arguable when reasonable people could disagree — it cannot be a fact (water boils at 100°C) or pure opinion (I like pizza). Strong claims are specific, debatable, and significant: 'Social media algorithms increase political polarization by rewarding outrage' is arguable; 'Social media is bad' is too vague.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"Distinguish between a line of reasoning and evidence. Why does an essay need both?","ex":"Think about structure and support.","a":"Line of reasoning: the logical structure of an argument — the sequence of claims that lead from evidence to thesis. Evidence: specific facts, examples, quotations, data that support the claims. You need both because evidence without reasoning is uninterpreted data; reasoning without evidence is unsupported assertion. Strong writing shows HOW and WHY the evidence supports the claim, not just that it does.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is concession and refutation, and how do they strengthen an argument?","ex":"Think about acknowledging the other side.","a":"Concession: acknowledging the validity of a counterargument or evidence that seems to undermine your position. Refutation: explaining why the counterargument is ultimately outweighed, limited, or wrong. Together they strengthen arguments because: (1) they show the writer has considered all perspectives (intellectual honesty → ethos); (2) they prevent the reader from dismissing the argument by thinking 'but what about X?'; (3) they demonstrate the writer's claim can withstand scrutiny.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is the difference between inductive and deductive reasoning?","ex":"Think about general to specific vs. specific to general.","a":"Deductive reasoning: starts with a general principle and applies it to a specific case (syllogism: All humans are mortal; Socrates is human; therefore Socrates is mortal). Valid if premises are true and logic is sound. Inductive reasoning: starts with specific observations and draws a general conclusion (I've observed 100 crows; all were black; therefore all crows are black). Inductive conclusions are probable, not certain — a single counterexample disproves them. Most real-world arguments blend both.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What are logical fallacies? Name and explain three.","ex":"Think about flawed reasoning patterns.","a":"Logical fallacies: errors in reasoning that make arguments invalid. (1) Ad hominem: attacking the person rather than the argument ('You can't trust their climate data — they're a liberal'). (2) Straw man: misrepresenting an opponent's argument to make it easier to attack ('They want to defund police — they want criminals running free'). (3) False dichotomy: presenting only two options when more exist ('You're either with us or against us'). Identifying fallacies is key to rhetorical analysis.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you analyze an author's tone and why does it matter for rhetorical effect?","ex":"Think about word choice, syntax, and emotional register.","a":"Tone: the author's attitude toward the subject and audience, conveyed through diction (word choice), syntax (sentence structure), imagery, and selection of details. Analyze by asking: what emotions does the language evoke? Are sentences short and punchy (urgency, anger) or long and complex (authority, thoughtfulness)? Is vocabulary formal or colloquial? Tone matters because it positions the audience and determines whether they receive the argument as credible, passionate, ironic, or authoritative.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is synthesis and how is it different from summarizing sources?","ex":"Think about creating an original argument from multiple sources.","a":"Synthesis: using multiple sources to construct and support an original argument — identifying connections, patterns, tensions, and implications across sources to build something new. Summarizing: simply restating what each source says. Synthesis requires the writer to be in control: sources serve the writer's argument, not the reverse. Key moves: comparing, contrasting, extending, complicating, challenging one source with another — all in service of a thesis.","diff":"hard"}
    ]},
    {"title":"Reasoning and Organization","problems":[
      {"q":"What is the purpose of an introduction in an AP Lang essay, and what should it accomplish?","ex":"Think about context, complexity, and thesis.","a":"A strong introduction: (1) Establishes context (broader situation that makes the argument relevant — more than just 'Since the beginning of time...'); (2) Moves from general to specific; (3) Presents a defensible, specific thesis that forecasts the argument. AP readers especially reward complexity — introductions that acknowledge nuance, tension, or competing perspectives before staking a position.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What are the three AP Lang free-response question types and what does each require?","ex":"Think about synthesis, analysis, and argument essays.","a":"(1) Synthesis (65 min): read 6–7 provided sources; write an essay arguing a position on a topic using at least 3 sources as evidence. (2) Rhetorical Analysis (40 min): analyze how a provided passage uses rhetorical strategies to achieve its purpose — identify devices, explain effect, connect to overall purpose. (3) Argument (40 min): write a defensible argument about a topic using evidence from your knowledge, reading, and experience.","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"Explain the difference between ethos, pathos, and logos with examples from real rhetoric.","ex":"Think about character, emotion, and logic.","a":"Ethos: appeals to credibility/character — 'As a doctor with 20 years of experience...' or citing expert sources. Pathos: appeals to emotion — vivid stories of individuals affected by a policy, powerful imagery, emotionally charged language. Logos: appeals to logic and reason — statistics, logical arguments, cause-and-effect reasoning, analogies. Effective rhetoric uses all three; overreliance on pathos alone without logos seems manipulative; logos without ethos seems detached.","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"What makes effective commentary on textual evidence? What should it do?","ex":"Think about what comes after you quote or cite.","a":"Commentary (also called analysis or explanation) explains: (1) WHAT the evidence shows — what it demonstrates about the subject; (2) HOW it supports the claim — the connection between evidence and assertion; (3) WHY it matters — the significance for the argument. Weak commentary: 'This shows that...' without explanation. Strong: explains the reasoning, interprets rather than restates, connects the specific detail to the broader argument. Rule of thumb: commentary should be at least as long as the evidence.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is the difference between content and style analysis in rhetorical analysis?","ex":"Think about what is said vs. how it is said.","a":"Content analysis examines WHAT the writer argues — claims, evidence, line of reasoning, logical structure. Style analysis examines HOW the writer argues — rhetorical strategies, diction, syntax, tone, figurative language, structure, appeals. AP Rhetorical Analysis requires both: identifying WHAT strategies are used AND explaining HOW and WHY they achieve rhetorical effect in the specific context. Naming a device (alliteration, anaphora) without explaining its effect earns minimal credit.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is style and how does syntax contribute to rhetorical effect in a passage?","ex":"Think about sentence length, structure, and patterns.","a":"Style: the choices a writer makes in language, sentence structure, tone, and organization to achieve effect. Syntax contributes: Short, declarative sentences → urgency, forcefulness, simplicity. Long, subordinate-clause-heavy sentences → complexity, qualification, elaboration. Parallel syntax (anaphora, epistrophe) → emphasis, rhythm, memorability. Inverted syntax (placing subject after verb) → surprise, emphasis on the inverted element. Sentence fragments → dramatic emphasis. Analyzing syntax means connecting these choices to their effect on the reader.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"How do you write a strong rhetorical analysis thesis?","ex":"Think about what it must include.","a":"A strong rhetorical analysis thesis identifies: (1) the author and context; (2) the specific rhetorical strategies used; (3) the purpose or effect those strategies achieve. Not strong: 'The author uses many rhetorical devices to persuade.' Strong: 'In her 1963 Senate testimony, Rachel Carson employs an appeal to scientific authority combined with understated irony to expose the chemical industry's willful ignorance and move her audience from complacency to outrage.' The thesis sets up the analysis and forecasts the argument.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What distinguishes a sophisticated argument from a basic one on the AP Lang exam?","ex":"Think about the complexity rubric point.","a":"Sophisticated arguments demonstrate: (1) Complexity — acknowledging tension, paradox, or qualifying the claim; (2) Consideration of alternative perspectives or counterarguments; (3) Explaining broader implications of the argument; (4) Developing a nuanced line of reasoning (not just listing points); (5) Using evidence that is specific and concrete (not vague generalizations). Sophistication is NOT about fancy vocabulary — it's about depth of thinking.","diff":"hard"}
    ]},
    {"title":"Style and Evidence","problems":[
      {"q":"What is diction and how does a writer's word choice reveal purpose and tone?","ex":"Think about formal vs. informal, denotation vs. connotation.","a":"Diction: choice of words. Formal/Latinate diction signals authority and seriousness. Colloquial/everyday diction creates accessibility or informality. Connotation (emotional associations of words) reveals attitude: 'activist' vs. 'agitator' — same denotation, opposite connotations. Elevated diction combined with simple syntax can create irony. Analyzing diction requires asking: why this word rather than a simpler or more complex alternative, and what effect does that choice produce?","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is anaphora and what rhetorical effect does it typically create?","ex":"Think about repetition at the beginning of clauses.","a":"Anaphora: repetition of a word or phrase at the beginning of successive clauses or sentences. Example: MLK's 'I have a dream...' repeated at the start of each vision. Effects: (1) creates rhythm and momentum; (2) builds emotional intensity; (3) emphasizes the repeated idea; (4) creates a sense of inevitability or accumulation. Anaphora is powerful in speeches because it's memorable and moves audiences emotionally. On the page, it creates structural emphasis.","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"What makes statistical evidence effective in an argumentative essay, and what are its limits?","ex":"Think about context, sourcing, and misuse.","a":"Effective statistics: specific, sourced, contextualized (what is the comparison group? What time period? Who collected the data?). Limits: correlation ≠ causation; sampling bias can skew data; statistics can be cherry-picked; averages can hide variation (median vs. mean); percentages without base numbers can mislead (a 50% increase from 2 to 3 cases). Statistics are most effective when combined with anecdotal evidence that humanizes the numbers and with explanation of what they mean.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is an extended analogy and when is it particularly effective in argumentation?","ex":"Think about comparing two unlike things to illuminate.","a":"An extended analogy: a sustained comparison between two unlike things that illuminates something unfamiliar or abstract by relating it to something familiar. Effective when: (1) the comparison accurately captures the essential relationship; (2) it helps an audience understand a complex idea quickly; (3) it generates emotional resonance. Limits: analogies can obscure differences — they simplify. A counterargument can point to ways the comparison breaks down. Effective arguers acknowledge the limits of their analogies.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"How should you integrate quotations smoothly into your own writing?","ex":"Think about introduction, citation, and commentary.","a":"The 'ICE' method: Introduce (provide context for who is speaking and why), Cite (quote accurately), Explain (analyze the quotation's significance). Never drop a quote without introduction ('According to Smith, '...'). Never let a quote end a paragraph — always follow with commentary. Vary your introductory verbs: argues, contends, observes, acknowledges, maintains. Match integration level to purpose: short quotation for precise language; paraphrase for main ideas; summary for background context.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is the AP Lang synthesis essay and how should you approach source selection?","ex":"Think about the 3-source minimum and how sources relate.","a":"The synthesis essay: you read 6-7 sources (text, graphs, images) and write an argument taking a position on a prompt, using evidence from at least 3 sources. Approach: (1) Read the prompt FIRST to know what argument you're building; (2) Annotate sources for what position they support or complicate; (3) Choose sources that create a CONVERSATION — agreement, disagreement, nuance; (4) Don't just cite sources — explain how they support your argument and engage their ideas; (5) Sources should serve YOUR thesis, not dictate it.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What role do transitions play in an argumentative essay?","ex":"Think about how ideas connect.","a":"Transitions signal logical relationships between ideas: addition (furthermore, moreover), contrast (however, nevertheless, yet), causation (therefore, consequently, as a result), concession (although, even though, while it's true that), sequence (first, subsequently, finally). Effective transitions: (1) connect the end of one paragraph to the start of the next; (2) show HOW ideas relate (not just 'another example is...'); (3) build momentum through the essay. Without them, an essay reads as a list of disconnected points rather than a unified argument.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you approach the AP Lang multiple choice section strategically?","ex":"Think about passage types, question stems, and elimination.","a":"Strategy: (1) Read the question stem carefully before rereading passage — know what you're looking for; (2) For rhetoric questions: identify device → explain effect → match to answer choice; (3) Eliminate clearly wrong answers; (4) For purpose questions: look at the whole passage's effect, not just one sentence; (5) 'Primarily' means the main purpose, not a minor one; (6) Answer in passage order when possible; (7) Trust close reading over memory — every answer is supported in the text; (8) For tone questions: find specific word choices that justify your answer.","diff":"medium"}
    ]},
    {"title":"Synthesis Essay","problems":[
      {"q":"Read this prompt paraphrase: 'Should social media companies be legally responsible for harmful content users post?' Write a thesis for a synthesis essay arguing they should be.","ex":"Make it specific and arguable.","a":"Sample thesis: 'Despite concerns about free expression, social media platforms should bear legal liability for harmful user content when they have profited from its spread, failed to act on reported violations, or algorithmically amplified it — because these conditions demonstrate active participation in harm rather than passive hosting.' This is specific (names conditions), arguable, and forecasts a nuanced line of reasoning.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is the difference between using a source as evidence and merely summarizing it in a synthesis essay?","ex":"Think about who controls the argument.","a":"Summarizing a source: you describe what the source says with minimal connection to your argument ('Source B says social media is harmful'). Using as evidence: you select specific elements of the source to support your claim and explain the connection ('Source B's data showing a 40% increase in teen anxiety correlates with smartphone adoption supports my claim that platforms must be regulated, since they profited during this period while ignoring documented harms'). In strong synthesis essays, the writer drives; sources are recruited, not just reported.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"How should you handle a source that seems to contradict your thesis in a synthesis essay?","ex":"Think about concession and refutation.","a":"Don't ignore it — AP readers notice cherry-picking. Acknowledge it directly: concede what's valid about the counterevidence, then explain why it doesn't defeat your thesis — it might be limited in scope, outweighed by other evidence, or addressing a different aspect of the issue. Example: 'Source D argues that government regulation stifles innovation. While this concern has merit in some contexts, it fails to account for the demonstrated harms documented in Sources A and C, where self-regulation has consistently failed.' This demonstrates complexity and intellectual honesty.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What does it mean to 'attribute' sources in the AP synthesis essay?","ex":"Think about signaling which source you're using.","a":"Attribution: making clear which source you're drawing from, without formal citation. Use phrases like: 'According to Source C...', 'The data in Source A suggests...', 'As Source E's author argues...' You don't need MLA citations — just clear attribution so the reader knows which source you're referencing. Unattributed claims are treated as your own unsupported assertions and lose synthesis credit.","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"What common mistakes do students make on the synthesis essay?","ex":"Think about what loses points.","a":"Common mistakes: (1) Writing a 'book report' — summarizing sources instead of arguing a position; (2) Ignoring the prompt — sources are a menu, not a script; (3) Using fewer than 3 sources; (4) Source-dumping — citing without explanation; (5) Treating all sources as equally credible (a student tweet vs. a CDC report); (6) Not having a clear thesis — starting with 'There are many perspectives on this issue'; (7) Weak or absent commentary explaining HOW sources support the argument.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you identify an author's purpose in a non-fiction passage for rhetorical analysis?","ex":"Think about what the author wants the reader to think, feel, or do.","a":"Purpose is the effect the author intends to produce on the audience. Ask: What does the author want the reader to believe, feel, or do after reading this? Common purposes: persuade (change attitude/behavior), inform (build understanding), entertain (engage), criticize (expose a flaw), celebrate/commemorate (honor), call to action (motivate). Purpose shapes every rhetorical choice. A political speech's purpose is persuasion; a eulogy's is to celebrate and comfort; an investigative article's is to expose and inform.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is the difference between paraphrasing and plagiarism in academic writing?","ex":"Think about changing words vs. changing ideas.","a":"Paraphrase: restating someone else's ideas in your own words and sentence structure, WITH attribution. You change the words AND structure while preserving the meaning — and you cite the source. Plagiarism: using someone else's words or ideas without attribution, OR changing only a few words while keeping the same structure (patchwriting). Even with attribution, patchwriting is considered inadequate paraphrase. Rule: if the idea is not common knowledge and not your own, attribute it.","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"What distinguishes a 'comment on effect' from 'naming a device' in rhetorical analysis?","ex":"Think about the difference between identifying and analyzing.","a":"Naming a device: 'The author uses anaphora.' This alone earns little AP credit — it's identification, not analysis. Commenting on effect: 'The author's anaphoric repetition of 'We will not' in successive clauses creates a drumbeat of resistance, building emotional intensity and signaling to the audience that the speaker's resolve is unconditional — inviting them to feel the same conviction.' The second version explains WHAT the device IS (anaphora), HOW it functions (repetition creating rhythm), and WHY it achieves the author's purpose (emotional intensity, audience identification).","diff":"hard"}
    ]},
    {"title":"Rhetorical Analysis Essay","problems":[
      {"q":"What structure should a rhetorical analysis essay follow?","ex":"Think about introduction, body, and conclusion purpose.","a":"Introduction: context (author, text, occasion), thesis that names key strategies and overall effect/purpose. Body paragraphs: each focused on one rhetorical strategy or a cluster of related choices — explain the strategy, provide specific evidence (quote/paraphrase), analyze HOW it creates the claimed effect and WHY that serves the author's purpose. Conclusion: synthesize the analysis — explain how strategies work together to achieve the overall purpose; consider implications or complexity. Throughout: keep the focus on HOW and WHY, not just WHAT.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you analyze how a graphic or visual functions rhetorically?","ex":"Think about composition, color, symbolism, and audience effect.","a":"Visual rhetoric analysis: examine composition (where is attention directed?), color (what associations/emotions?), symbolism (what does the image represent?), selection (what is included or excluded?), juxtaposition (what is placed near what?), and caption-image relationship. Ask: what argument or emotional response does this image advance? Who is the intended audience? How does it use ethos, pathos, or logos? A photograph of a suffering child in an ad makes an emotional (pathos) argument; a clean infographic makes a logical (logos) one.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"Explain how sentence-level choices (syntax) can be analyzed rhetorically.","ex":"Give specific examples of syntax choices and their effects.","a":"Syntax analysis examples: Periodic sentence (main clause at end) → creates suspense, forces reader to hold ideas in tension before resolution. Cumulative sentence (main clause first, then elaboration) → natural, additive, open-ended. Asyndeton (omitting conjunctions: 'I came, I saw, I conquered') → speed, force, compression. Polysyndeton (many conjunctions: 'and...and...and') → accumulation, slowness, abundance. Inverted syntax → emphasis on the displaced element. The key: always connect the syntactic choice to its rhetorical effect on the audience.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is the difference between rhetoric about the text vs. rhetoric in the text?","ex":"Think about what the essay describes.","a":"Rhetoric IN the text: the actual strategies the author uses — metaphors, appeals, syntax, diction, structure. Rhetoric ABOUT the text: what YOU do in your essay — how you organize, what you claim, how you support your analysis. A common mistake is confusing the two: writing a well-organized essay (your rhetoric) while only summarizing what the passage says (not analyzing the passage's rhetoric). The assignment is to analyze the author's rhetorical choices in the text, not to argue about the topic the text addresses.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"How do you avoid the 'list of devices' trap in rhetorical analysis?","ex":"Think about what makes analysis shallow.","a":"The list trap: 'The author uses alliteration, metaphor, and repetition.' This names devices without analysis. Avoidance strategies: (1) Ask 'to what effect?' after naming every device; (2) Organize by purpose or effect rather than by device (not 'The author uses ethos...then pathos...' but 'To establish credibility...'...then 'To move the audience emotionally...'); (3) Use evidence that is specifically chosen to illustrate the claim; (4) Make sure each paragraph has a controlling claim about how a strategy works, not just what it is.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How should you handle an author's use of irony in a rhetorical analysis?","ex":"Think about what irony does rhetorically.","a":"Irony: saying the opposite of what is meant (verbal irony), or a situation where outcome contradicts expectation (situational), or dramatic irony (audience knows more than character). In rhetorical analysis: identify the gap between surface meaning and intended meaning → explain what the author is actually arguing → analyze WHY the author chose indirection (irony can create distance, avoid direct accusation, invite audience to feel clever for 'getting it,' make criticism more palatable or more devastating). Swift's 'A Modest Proposal' is pure irony — the shocking surface makes the real argument more powerful by contrast.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is the rhetorical effect of addressing the audience directly?","ex":"Think about second-person pronouns and direct address.","a":"Direct address (second-person 'you,' apostrophe to a group) creates immediacy and implicates the reader personally. It breaks the boundary between text and reader, making the audience feel addressed rather than observed. Rhetorical effects: (1) Increases urgency — 'You must act now'; (2) Creates community or exclusion — 'Those of you who care about justice...'; (3) Can be accusatory or flattering; (4) Shifts from abstract to personal — makes the issue feel relevant to this specific reader's life. Speeches use it to create shared identity between speaker and audience.","diff":"medium"}
    ]},
    {"title":"Argument Essay","problems":[
      {"q":"What evidence types are available for the AP Lang argument essay?","ex":"Think about what counts as evidence when no sources are provided.","a":"Evidence types (no sources provided — you bring your own): (1) Historical examples — specific events, people, movements; (2) Literary/artistic examples — works you've studied; (3) Scientific or statistical knowledge — studies, data you know; (4) Current events; (5) Personal experience (used sparingly, when it genuinely illustrates the principle); (6) Logical reasoning — thought experiments, analogies, logical implications. Quality over quantity: one well-developed, specific example is stronger than three vague ones.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you write a compelling argument essay without provided sources?","ex":"Think about what makes the argument stand on its own.","a":"Strategy: (1) Read prompt carefully — understand exactly what you're arguing about; (2) Take a clear position immediately (not 'It depends'); (3) Develop 2-3 reasons with specific, developed evidence; (4) Anticipate and address counterarguments; (5) Show complexity — qualify your claim if needed ('While X may be true in some contexts, the evidence shows...'); (6) Maintain consistent point of view; (7) Strong opening that doesn't just restate the prompt; (8) Conclusion that extends the argument rather than merely restating it.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What does 'complexity' look like in an argument essay?","ex":"Think about what distinguishes the top score.","a":"Complexity in argument: (1) Acknowledging and engaging with the strongest counterargument; (2) Qualifying the claim — specifying conditions under which it's more or less true; (3) Explaining tensions within the issue (two values that conflict); (4) Addressing multiple perspectives that don't fit neatly into 'for/against'; (5) Explaining broader implications of your argument; (6) Exploring why the issue is genuinely difficult. Complexity is NOT hedging until you have no position — it's having a clear position while demonstrating you understand the issue's genuine difficulty.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"How should you develop an analogy as evidence in an argument essay?","ex":"Think about how analogy works as reasoning.","a":"An effective analogy in argument: (1) Clearly identifies the two things being compared; (2) Explains WHAT specific features make them comparable; (3) Shows how the principle in the familiar case applies to the unfamiliar case you're arguing; (4) Acknowledges limits if needed. Weak analogy: 'This is like [similar thing].' Strong: 'Like the FDA's requirement that drug companies prove safety before marketing, social media platforms should be required to assess harm before algorithmically amplifying content — in both cases, the scale of potential harm justifies requiring proactive responsibility rather than reactive correction.'","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What are the most common errors in AP Lang argument essays?","ex":"Think about what loses points in scoring.","a":"Common errors: (1) No clear thesis or a thesis that just says 'both sides have merit'; (2) Evidence is vague/general ('many studies show...') without specific examples; (3) No development — just listing reasons without explanation; (4) Ignoring the counterargument entirely; (5) Circular reasoning — using the claim as its own evidence; (6) Overgeneralization — claiming something is always true without qualification; (7) Weak conclusion that just restates the introduction; (8) Going off-topic into tangentially related issues.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you calibrate your claim to available evidence?","ex":"Think about what you can actually support.","a":"Claim calibration: match the strength of your claim to the evidence you can provide. 'Social media always causes depression' is harder to support than 'There is significant evidence linking heavy social media use in adolescents to increased depression rates.' Strong arguers make claims they can fully support and signal limitations honestly: 'While this argument focuses on the US context, similar patterns have been documented in...' A well-supported modest claim is stronger than an oversweeping claim with weak evidence.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What makes a conclusion effective in an argument essay?","ex":"Think about what goes beyond restatement.","a":"Effective conclusions: (1) Don't merely restate the introduction — elevate the argument; (2) Address broader implications: what does your argument mean beyond this specific case? (3) Call to action (if appropriate): what should readers do or think differently? (4) Circle back to the opening with new insight; (5) Acknowledge remaining complexity or unanswered questions; (6) End with a memorable sentence — often a short, declarative statement or a compelling image. Weak conclusion: 'In conclusion, for these reasons, I have shown...' followed by a summary.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How does the AP Lang scoring rubric evaluate the argument essay?","ex":"Think about the three main categories.","a":"AP Lang argument essay rubric: (1) Thesis (0-1 pt): defensible, specific claim — not merely a restatement of the prompt. (2) Evidence and Commentary (0-4 pts): 1=merely restates thesis; 2=provides evidence with little/no commentary; 3=provides evidence with adequate commentary; 4=consistently effective, well-developed evidence with insightful commentary. (3) Sophistication (0-1 pt): demonstrates complexity of thought — qualifying claim, addressing tensions, explaining implications, using particularly effective rhetoric. Maximum: 6 points.","diff":"medium"}
    ]},
    {"title":"Close Reading Non-Fiction","problems":[
      {"q":"What does 'close reading' mean and how do you do it for a non-fiction passage?","ex":"Think about reading with attention to language, not just meaning.","a":"Close reading: reading attentively at the word, sentence, and structure level — noticing HOW meaning is made, not just WHAT is meant. Process: (1) Read for gist (what is this about?); (2) Reread slowly — annotate: underline significant words, mark rhetorical devices, note shifts in tone or argument; (3) Ask: why this word? Why this structure? Why this order? What is the effect on the reader? (4) Look for patterns — recurring images, sentence types, appeals; (5) Connect choices to purpose and audience. Close reading reveals intentionality behind every linguistic choice.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you identify shifts in a passage and why are they rhetorically significant?","ex":"Think about tone shifts, argument pivots, and structural turns.","a":"Shifts: moments where something changes — tone (from personal to formal), purpose (from narrative to argument), subject (from specific to general), syntax (from complex to simple), speaker's position (from objective to impassioned). Locating shifts: look for transition words, changes in pronoun use, changes in sentence length or complexity, introduction of new subjects. Significance: shifts signal what the author considers most important; they often mark the emotional or argumentative climax; they reveal the structure of the argument.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How does organizational structure itself function rhetorically?","ex":"Think about how order creates meaning.","a":"Structural choices create rhetorical effect: Beginning with narrative then moving to argument: establishes emotional connection before rational argument → audience is primed to care. Building from specific to general: grounds abstract claims in concrete reality. Chiastic structure (A-B-B-A): creates symmetry and memorability. Ending with the strongest evidence: most recent, leaves biggest impression. Juxtaposition of sections (wealth vs. poverty, past vs. present): contrast emphasizes difference. The organizational architecture of a text is itself an argument about what matters most.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is the difference between a claim about subject matter and a claim about rhetoric?","ex":"Think about WHAT vs. HOW.","a":"Subject matter claim: 'The author argues that climate change is an existential threat.' This describes the content. Rhetorical claim: 'The author uses catastrophic imagery to move the audience from intellectual acknowledgment to emotional urgency about climate change.' This describes HOW the argument is constructed and its intended effect. Rhetorical analysis requires rhetorical claims — not just content summary. The test: could your claim be written without reading the text closely for language? If yes, it's a content claim, not a rhetorical one.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you analyze use of evidence within a primary text (how an author argues)?","ex":"Think about what types of evidence the author uses and why.","a":"When analyzing how an author uses evidence: (1) Identify what kind of evidence the author deploys (statistics, anecdotes, expert testimony, historical examples, personal narrative); (2) Explain why that evidence type is appropriate for the audience and purpose; (3) Analyze how the evidence is framed — does the author contextualize, interpret, or let it 'speak for itself'? (4) Evaluate placement — does difficult evidence appear after establishing trust? (5) Note what evidence is absent — strategic omissions are rhetorical too.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is a subtext and how do you identify it in non-fiction?","ex":"Think about what is implied but not stated.","a":"Subtext: meaning implied beneath the surface of a text — what the author communicates without stating directly. Identification: look for what the author doesn't say but assumes the audience knows or believes; look for irony, understatement, or euphemism; look for who is addressed and who is excluded; look for what the argument needs to be true but doesn't prove. In political rhetoric, subtext often carries ideological assumptions. Example: 'law-abiding citizens deserve protection' subtextually implies a distinction between law-abiding and non-law-abiding that does significant rhetorical work.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"How does understanding historical context improve rhetorical analysis?","ex":"Think about how context shapes meaning.","a":"Historical context illuminates: (1) Why this argument was being made at this moment — the exigence; (2) What the audience already believed — what needed to be said vs. what could be assumed; (3) What the risks were for the author — speaking against power requires different strategies than speaking with it; (4) The specific occasions, events, or debates the text responds to. Example: Lincoln's Second Inaugural Address can only be understood knowing the Civil War was nearly over — the conciliatory tone ('malice toward none') responds to that specific moment. Decontextualized analysis misses crucial dimensions.","diff":"medium"}
    ]},
    {"title":"Tone, Diction, and Syntax Analysis","problems":[
      {"q":"What distinguishes 'tone' from 'mood'?","ex":"Think about speaker vs. reader emotion.","a":"Tone: the author's or speaker's attitude toward the subject and/or audience — revealed through diction, syntax, and stylistic choices. Mood: the emotional atmosphere created in the reader/audience. A writer can maintain a detached, clinical tone (author's attitude = objective) while creating a deeply unsettling mood (reader's feeling = disturbed). A satirical text may have a playful, ironic tone while creating a mood of uncomfortable recognition. Both are worth analyzing; don't conflate them.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you analyze a list or catalog device for rhetorical effect?","ex":"Think about what lists accomplish beyond their content.","a":"Lists (catalog/enumeration): accumulate examples or details with intensity. Effects: (1) Abundance — sheer quantity creates sense of overwhelming evidence or excess; (2) Pattern — if items are similar, creates expectation and monotony (can be satirical); (3) Disruption — if one item breaks the pattern, creates comic or tragic surprise; (4) Democratic equity — listing together things of different status implies equivalence; (5) Breathlessness — asyndeton lists (no conjunctions) create rapid pace. Ask: what is being accumulated? Why here? What is the effect of juxtaposition within the list?","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is understatement (litotes) and when does an author use it for rhetorical effect?","ex":"Think about saying less than what is meant.","a":"Understatement: deliberately describing something as less significant than it is. Litotes: understatement through double negation ('not unhappy'). Rhetorical effects: (1) Creates irony when the gap between statement and reality is obvious; (2) Conveys sophistication or restraint — not stooping to hyperbole; (3) Can intensify impact by making the reader fill in the gap; (4) In British political discourse, is a mark of credibility. Example: calling the Holocaust 'unpleasant' would be devastating understatement making the offense obvious by contrast.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"How does figurative language function in a rhetorical (non-literary) text?","ex":"Think about what metaphors do in argument.","a":"Figurative language in rhetoric: (1) Metaphor makes abstract concepts tangible ('The economy is an engine that stalls without fuel'); (2) Personification creates emotional connection to abstract forces; (3) Vivid simile creates concrete mental imagery that makes arguments memorable; (4) Analogies help audiences understand unfamiliar issues through familiar comparisons. In non-fiction/rhetoric, figurative language isn't decoration — it does argumentative work by framing the issue in a particular way that advantages the author's position. The frame (metaphor) constrains how readers think about the subject.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is parallel structure and how does it function rhetorically?","ex":"Think about grammatical balance and what it creates.","a":"Parallel structure: grammatically equivalent elements placed in a series. Rhetorical effects: (1) Balance and equivalence — parallel elements are presented as equal in importance; (2) Rhythm and memorability ('life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness'); (3) Emphasis through repetition of structure; (4) Clarity through consistent grammatical form. Broken parallelism (one item not grammatically equivalent) stands out as either an error or a deliberate emphasis strategy. In speeches and declarations, parallelism is fundamental to their power: 'We shall fight on the beaches, we shall fight on the landing grounds...'","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How should you annotate a passage during the AP Lang exam?","ex":"Think about what to mark and why.","a":"Annotation strategy: (1) Underline key phrases that reveal tone, purpose, or argument; (2) Mark rhetorical devices in the margin with brief labels AND a word about effect; (3) Number or bracket sections — where does the argument shift?; (4) Circle recurring words or images (patterns); (5) Star the thesis/central claim; (6) Write a one-word tone label at each paragraph; (7) Mark evidence types (anecdote, statistic, analogy). Don't over-annotate — mark what you'll actually use. The goal: when writing the analysis, you can find evidence quickly without re-reading the whole passage.","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"What is the difference between a rhetorical question and a loaded question?","ex":"Think about the intended response.","a":"Rhetorical question: asked for effect, not to elicit a response — the answer is implied or obvious ('Who could oppose justice?'). Functions: emphasize a point, involve the audience, challenge assumptions. Loaded question: presupposes something contestable in its framing ('Have you stopped cheating?') — any answer accepts the presupposition. In rhetoric, loaded questions smuggle assumptions into the discourse. Rhetorical questions invite agreement; loaded questions trap the respondent. Both are worth analyzing for what they reveal about the author's argument and assumptions.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How does the register of a text (formal vs. informal) function rhetorically?","ex":"Think about who register includes and excludes.","a":"Register: level of formality in language. Formal register: Latin-derived vocabulary, complex syntax, impersonal tone → signals expertise, authority, serious purpose; aligns with institutional power; may exclude general audiences. Informal/colloquial register: everyday language, contractions, conversational syntax → creates accessibility and intimacy; aligns with common experience; risks seeming unprepared or unserious in professional contexts. Strategic register mixing (formal argument + colloquial aside) can create humor, irony, or inclusivity. Register choice reveals the audience the author assumes and the ethos they want to project.","diff":"hard"}
    ]}
  ],
  # Unit 2 — AP English Literature and Composition
  [
    {"title":"Short Fiction and Prose","problems":[
      {"q":"What is the difference between first-person, second-person, and third-person narration, and how does each affect reader experience?","ex":"Think about intimacy, distance, and reliability.","a":"First-person (I/we): intimate, direct access to narrator's thoughts; but limited perspective (only sees what narrator sees/knows); reliability is always questionable. Second-person (you): creates direct address, implicates reader, creates disorientation — uncommon, often experimental. Third-person limited (he/she/they, one character's perspective): narrator reports one character's inner life; reader sees world through that lens. Third-person omniscient: narrator has access to all characters' thoughts and events; provides breadth and perspective. Each creates different distance between reader and character.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is an unreliable narrator and what are the signals that a narrator may be unreliable?","ex":"Think about gaps, contradictions, and self-interest.","a":"Unreliable narrator: a narrator whose account cannot be fully trusted — due to limited knowledge, mental instability, deliberate deception, or self-interested interpretation. Signals: (1) Contradictions between what narrator says and what events show; (2) Other characters' reactions that don't match narrator's interpretation; (3) Narrator has obvious motive to deceive; (4) Missing information the narrator should know; (5) Narrator's self-glorification at others' expense. Examples: Stevens in Remains of the Day, Nick Carraway in Gatsby (arguably), the governess in Turn of the Screw.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is in medias res and why do authors use it?","ex":"Think about where the story begins.","a":"In medias res (Latin: 'in the middle of things'): beginning a narrative in the midst of action, before the backstory is provided — then revealing context through flashback or gradual disclosure. Effects: (1) Creates immediate engagement and tension; (2) Trusts the reader to piece together context; (3) Avoids slow exposition; (4) Makes the reader an active participant in constructing meaning. Homer's Iliad and Odyssey begin in medias res. Many modern short stories begin this way — the reader is dropped into a scene and must orient themselves.","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"How do you analyze setting as more than mere background?","ex":"Think about setting as symbolic, atmospheric, or deterministic.","a":"Setting functions as: (1) Atmosphere — weather, season, and environment establish emotional tone (a swamp suggests decay; a bright morning suggests possibility); (2) Symbol — a specific location can represent abstract ideas (the green light in Gatsby, the moors in Wuthering Heights); (3) Social context — setting reveals class, cultural, and historical constraints on characters; (4) Character reflection — landscape can mirror character's inner state (pathetic fallacy); (5) Deterministic force — some authors treat setting as shaping or trapping characters (naturalist fiction).","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is Chekhov's Gun and how does it apply to analyzing short fiction?","ex":"Think about what details matter.","a":"Chekhov's Gun: the principle that every element introduced in a story must be relevant — if a gun appears in Act 1, it must fire by Act 3. In analysis: every specific detail an author includes is presumably intentional. When analyzing short fiction, pay attention to what is specifically described (color, object, name) because these are likely to be symbolically or thematically significant. The opposite of this principle is red herring — deliberate inclusion of misleading details. Either way, significant details reward close attention.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What does it mean to analyze a story's structure?","ex":"Think about plot order and what choices reveal.","a":"Story structure analysis: (1) Linear/chronological: events in temporal order — suggests causality, inevitability; (2) Non-linear/fragmented: time shuffled — suggests memory, trauma, or complexity of causation; (3) Frame narrative: story within a story — raises questions about perspective and interpretation; (4) Circular structure: story ends where it began — suggests entrapment, irony, or completion of a cycle. Also analyze: where does the story begin and why? Where does it end and what is left unresolved? What is the story's climax and what does it reveal about theme?","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is epiphany in fiction and how does it contribute to theme?","ex":"Think about the character's moment of realization.","a":"Epiphany (Joyce's term): a character's sudden realization of truth about themselves or the world — a moment of insight that is often quietly devastating or illuminating. Contributes to theme: the nature of the epiphany reveals what the story is 'about' — what it claims about human experience. In Dubliners, characters achieve partial epiphanies about their paralysis without necessarily escaping it — which itself is the thematic statement. The epiphany is often the story's climax, even if nothing externally dramatic occurs.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you analyze an author's choice of significant detail in a prose passage?","ex":"Think about what's selected vs. omitted.","a":"Significant detail analysis: (1) What exactly is described — the precision and specificity of details signals importance; (2) What is NOT described — omissions are also meaningful (what does the author skip over?); (3) Sensory register — which senses are engaged (visual, auditory, tactile) and to what effect?; (4) Connotative weight — what associations do specific words carry?; (5) Frequency — repeated details are emphasized; (6) Juxtaposition — what details are placed beside each other to create contrast or irony? Details are never neutral — selection is already interpretation.","diff":"hard"}
    ]},
    {"title":"Poetry Analysis","problems":[
      {"q":"What is the difference between form and content in poetry and why should you analyze both?","ex":"Think about what the poem says vs. how it says it.","a":"Content: what the poem is 'about' — subject matter, imagery, narrative, argument. Form: how the poem is organized — structure (sonnet, villanelle, free verse), line breaks, stanza patterns, meter, rhyme. The most sophisticated poetry analysis shows how form and content work together — how the form enacts or complicates the content. Example: a sonnet about fleeting love that follows the sonnet's traditional turn (volta) formally mirrors the emotional shift it describes. Form is not decoration — it is meaning.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is a volta and how do you identify it in a sonnet?","ex":"Think about the turn in argument or emotion.","a":"Volta: the turn or shift in a sonnet — a change in argument, tone, perspective, or emotional register. In a Petrarchan sonnet (14 lines: 8+6): the volta typically occurs at line 9 (between octave and sestet). In a Shakespearean sonnet (14 lines: 4+4+4+2): the volta often occurs in the final couplet, which pivots, resolves, or complicates the preceding three quatrains. The volta is rarely just a turn in content — it represents a shift in the poem's epistemological or emotional stance.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How does enjambment function differently from end-stopped lines?","ex":"Think about how line breaks create or deny closure.","a":"End-stopped line: line ends with punctuation — creates pause, closure, or completion at the line boundary; reader rests. Enjambment: line continues past the end without punctuation into the next line — creates forward momentum; the meaning is withheld until the next line; creates tension between syntactic unit and poetic line. Poets use enjambment to: create ambiguity (a word at line-end can mean two things before the line turns); accelerate pace; create irony (what sounds complete at line-end is complicated by the continuation); enact instability or continuity.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is the difference between a poem's speaker and the poet? Why does this distinction matter?","ex":"Think about dramatic monologue.","a":"Poet: the actual author — a real person with a life and biography. Speaker: the persona or voice constructed within the poem — may be fully distinct from the poet (as in dramatic monologue: Browning's 'My Last Duchess' speaker is a murderous duke, not Browning). Distinction matters: reading the speaker's statements as the poet's direct views can lead to biographical fallacy (judging the poem by the author's life). Analysis should address what the speaker reveals about themselves, how the speaker is constructed, and what that construction means — not what the poet 'really believed.'","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you analyze imagery clusters in a poem?","ex":"Think about patterns of related images.","a":"Imagery cluster: a network of related images throughout a poem — all drawn from the same sensory or conceptual domain (water images, mechanical images, darkness images). Analysis: (1) Identify recurring image domain; (2) Trace how individual images relate to each other; (3) Analyze what associations the cluster creates (water → fluidity, cleansing, drowning, life, time); (4) Ask how the cluster develops or shifts across the poem; (5) Connect to theme — what does the cluster suggest about what the poem is 'about.' Clusters create coherence even in free verse poems without formal structure.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is meter and how does deviation from the expected meter create meaning?","ex":"Think about iambic pentameter and variations.","a":"Meter: the rhythmic pattern of stressed and unstressed syllables. Iambic pentameter: five iambs (da-DUM) per line — the dominant meter of English poetry (Shakespeare, Milton, Keats). Deviation: a spondee (two stresses: DUM-DUM), trochee (DUM-da), or pyrrhic (da-da) substituted for an iamb. Effect: metrical deviation draws attention — the stress pattern breaks, making the reader pause on that word. A spondee on a key word ('DARK, DARK, DARK' in Milton) creates weight and emphasis. Analysis of meter requires scanning (marking stressed/unstressed syllables) and explaining why deviations occur where they do.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"""How do you write a strong poetry analysis thesis?""","ex":"""Think about what it must claim.""","a":"""Strong poetry analysis thesis makes a specific, arguable claim about WHAT the poem does and HOW it does it. Not strong: 'This poem is about loss and uses figurative language.' Strong: 'In "One Art," Bishop transforms the grammar of the villanelle's refrain into a structural argument — the accumulating losses across stanzas force the refrain's breezy assertion to collapse under its own irony, making the poem a performance of the very denial it diagnoses.' The thesis should name: (1) the key poetic strategies; (2) the effect or argument those strategies create; (3) something specific about HOW form and content interact.""","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is the difference between a poem's subject and its theme?","ex":"Think about what the poem is 'about' at two levels.","a":"Subject: what the poem literally addresses — death of a friend, a walk in snow, a painting. Theme: the larger claim the poem makes about human experience through that subject — 'love persists despite time,' 'beauty and decay are inseparable,' 'language cannot capture grief.' Subjects are specific; themes are universal or broadly applicable. Weak analysis states the subject ('This poem is about a snowy evening'); strong analysis articulates the theme ('Frost uses the snowy evening to explore how ordinary obligations interrupt the human impulse toward surrender and oblivion').","diff":"medium"}
    ]},
    {"title":"Longer Fiction and Drama","problems":[
      {"q":"What is the difference between static and dynamic characters, and flat vs. round characters?","ex":"Think about two different dimensions of character.","a":"Dynamic: characters who change significantly over the course of the narrative (Ebenezer Scrooge, Elizabeth Bennet). Static: characters who remain essentially the same (some supporting characters whose function is to represent a fixed quality). Round: characters with psychological complexity, apparent contradictions, inner life — feel like real people. Flat: characters defined by one or two dominant traits, often functional or symbolic (the scheming villain, the wise mentor). Dynamic/static = about change; round/flat = about complexity. Great novels often have dynamic, round protagonists and purposefully flat foils.","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"How do you analyze dramatic irony and its effect on the audience?","ex":"Think about what the audience knows vs. what characters know.","a":"Dramatic irony: audience knows something a character doesn't — creates tension, pathos, or dark comedy. Effects: (1) Suspense — we dread what's coming; (2) Pathos — our superior knowledge makes a character's innocence or hope especially moving; (3) Dark comedy — gap between character's confidence and audience's knowledge creates humor; (4) Moral insight — we see the character's choices differently than they do. Examples: Oedipus pursuing his own ruin; Romeo not knowing Juliet is alive; we watch knowing what they don't.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is the significance of the tragic hero's hamartia?","ex":"Think about the fatal flaw in Greek and Shakespearean tragedy.","a":"Hamartia (often translated as 'tragic flaw'): the characteristic or error in judgment that leads to the tragic hero's downfall. Aristotle's insight: the hamartia is often closely related to the hero's greatest virtue — Oedipus's intelligence and determination lead him to pursue truth until it destroys him; Macbeth's ambition that makes him great also makes him ruthless. The tragic hero's destruction is not random — it's structurally generated by who they are. This generates catharsis (pity and fear) because we see both greatness and vulnerability.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is an archetype and how do archetypes function in literature?","ex":"Think about recurring patterns (Jung, Campbell).","a":"Archetype: a recurrent character type, plot pattern, or symbolic image that appears across cultures and literary traditions — rooted in universal human experience. Examples: hero's journey (call to adventure, ordeal, return), trickster (Loki, Puck, Anansi), the shadow (embodiment of everything the hero represses), death-and-rebirth motif. Archetypes function by activating deep recognition in readers and generating expectations that authors can fulfill or subvert. Recognizing archetypes illuminates a text's relationship to the broader tradition — and where it departs from expectation reveals its specific argument.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you analyze the function of foil characters?","ex":"Think about contrast and what it reveals.","a":"Foil: a character whose traits contrast with those of the protagonist, making the protagonist's qualities stand out more clearly. Analysis: (1) Identify specific contrasting traits (Hamlet's hesitation vs. Laertes' immediate action); (2) Explain what the contrast reveals about the protagonist that wouldn't be visible without it; (3) Consider whether the foil is merely functional or also has independent complexity; (4) Ask what the author's purpose is — what does the comparison between them contribute to the work's theme? Foils aren't just 'different' — they illuminate something essential.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is social class as a theme in literary fiction and how do authors dramatize it?","ex":"Think about how class is shown rather than told.","a":"Authors dramatize class through: (1) Characters' language — dialect, vocabulary, verbal register signal class; (2) Physical space — who has access to what rooms, buildings, neighborhoods; (3) Objects and possessions — what characters own, desire, or are excluded from; (4) Gaze — who observes and who is observed; (5) Marriage and social mobility — who can marry whom and with what consequences; (6) Work — what labor characters do and how it's valued. Key texts: Dickens, Austen, Hardy, Fitzgerald, contemporary fiction. Class is rarely stated directly — it's enacted through these registers.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is a symbol and how do you distinguish a genuine symbol from a convenient object?","ex":"Think about what makes something resonate beyond itself.","a":"Symbol: an object, person, setting, or event that stands for something beyond its literal meaning — resonates with significance rooted in the work's structure and the larger cultural context. A genuine symbol: (1) appears repeatedly or at crucial moments; (2) is described with unusual attention; (3) its meaning emerges from context — not imposed by the reader; (4) connects to multiple aspects of theme. A convenient object: mentioned once, merely functional. Test: can you remove it without losing meaning? Can you articulate specifically what it represents? Can you trace how the text establishes its symbolic significance?","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How does an open ending differ from an ambiguous ending in fiction?","ex":"Think about what is unresolved and why.","a":"Open ending: genuinely does not resolve the central conflict — the reader is left uncertain about what happens. The openness is deliberate: it implicates the reader in creating meaning, or suggests the world doesn't offer neat resolutions. Ambiguous ending: events are shown but their meaning or interpretation is left open — we know what happens but not what it means. Both differ from a cliffhanger (which promises resolution). Analyzing why an author chose an open or ambiguous ending: what would have been lost by resolution? What does the inconclusiveness suggest about theme?","diff":"medium"}
    ]},
    {"title":"Character, Setting, Structure","problems":[
      {"q":"What is characterization and what techniques do authors use to reveal character?","ex":"Think about direct vs. indirect.","a":"Direct characterization: the narrator or another character explicitly describes a character ('She was selfish and calculating'). Indirect characterization: character is revealed through action, dialogue, thoughts, reaction of others, and physical appearance — the reader infers character. STEAL acronym for indirect: Speech (what they say and how), Thoughts, Effect on others, Actions, Looks. Literary fiction relies heavily on indirect characterization — it creates the sense of discovery and interpretation rather than being told.","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"How does the setting of a literary work contribute to its thematic meaning?","ex":"Give an example connecting setting to theme.","a":"Setting as thematic: The Great Gatsby's West Egg/East Egg geography externalizes the class distinction between old and new money — physical space embodies social reality. The waste land between West Egg and New York represents the moral desolation beneath the glamour. In One Hundred Years of Solitude, Macondo's isolation embodies the solitude and repetition that define human existence. When analyzing setting, ask: what does this place represent? What constraints does it impose? How does it reflect or contrast with the characters' internal states?","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is narrative distance and how does it affect interpretation?","ex":"Think about close vs. distant narration.","a":"Narrative distance: how close the narrator is to the events and characters being described. Close (psychic distance: low): we're inside a character's consciousness — free indirect discourse, stream of consciousness — maximum intimacy and subjectivity. Distant (psychic distance: high): narrator reports from outside, with detachment — creates irony, objectivity, or coldness. Authors modulate distance: zooming in for intimate moments (emotional access), zooming out for ironic perspective (critical distance). Analyzing distance: find moments where it shifts and ask why — what is being granted or withheld?","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is free indirect discourse and what does it allow in third-person narration?","ex":"Think about blending narrator and character voice.","a":"Free indirect discourse: a technique that blends third-person narration with first-person character perspective — the narrator reports a character's thoughts in third person but without 'she thought' or 'he felt' attribution. Example (Austen): 'It was a truth universally acknowledged...' — whose 'truth'? The irony works because we can't be sure if the narrator believes it or is reporting a character's/society's belief. FID allows: interior access without formal attribution, irony through distance, polyphony (multiple voices in one passage), immersion in character consciousness.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"How does a framing narrative affect interpretation of the embedded story?","ex":"Think about Heart of Darkness or Canterbury Tales.","a":"Framing narrative: a story that contains another story — Marlow's tale in Heart of Darkness is framed by an outer narrator on a boat. Effects: (1) Raises questions about reliability — how does the frame narrator receive and transmit the inner story? (2) Creates temporal distance — the inner story is already past; (3) The frame can ironize the embedded narrative; (4) The frame narrator's responses guide reader interpretation; (5) The act of storytelling itself becomes thematic. Heart of Darkness: Marlow's story is filtered through a narrator who frames Marlow's ambiguity — we must interpret Marlow's interpretation.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is the significance of a work's title and how can it function as a key to interpretation?","ex":"Think about what titles reveal or withhold.","a":"Title functions: (1) Thematic announcement ('The Age of Innocence' — the title's irony becomes clear when innocence is revealed as willed blindness); (2) Symbol identification ('The Scarlet Letter' — the object and what it represents are the text); (3) Character name — centers the work on individual experience; (4) Setting or time — situates the work; (5) Allusion — invokes another text's meanings; (6) Irony or paradox — creates expectation that the work will subvert. Analyzing titles: ask what the title assumes the reader knows, what it promises, and whether the work delivers, subverts, or complicates that promise.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How does analyzing the first and last sentences of a novel or story reveal its concerns?","ex":"Think about what opening and closing emphasize.","a":"Opening sentence: establishes voice, narrative contract (what kind of story is this?), tone, narrative distance, and often the central concern or tension. 'Call me Ishmael' (Moby Dick) — the name and the command both signal performance and mystery. Closing sentence: enacts or denies resolution; often circles back to opening or image (circular structure); may withhold or crystallize meaning. Analyzing both together: what has changed? What hasn't? What is left unresolved? What did the text promise in the opening, and how does the closing fulfill, complicate, or deny that promise?","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is verisimilitude and why do some works deliberately reject it?","ex":"Think about realistic vs. anti-realistic fiction.","a":"Verisimilitude: the appearance of being true or real — realistic fiction creates a believable world with psychologically consistent characters, plausible cause-and-effect, recognizable social contexts. Some works deliberately reject verisimilitude (magical realism, absurdism, postmodern metafiction) to: defamiliarize the real (make us see familiar things strangely), reveal the artificiality of realism's conventions, explore reality's deeper truth through the unreal, or comment on the act of storytelling itself. The question is always: what does realism or its rejection contribute to the work's meaning?","diff":"hard"}
    ]},
    {"title":"Figurative Language and Literary Devices","problems":[
      {"q":"What is the difference between a metaphor, simile, and analogy?","ex":"Think about direct comparison vs. 'like/as' vs. extended comparison.","a":"Simile: explicit comparison using 'like' or 'as' ('Her voice was like music'). Metaphor: direct identification of one thing with another ('Her voice is music'). More compressed, more complete merging. Analogy: extended comparison used to explain or argue a point — less poetic, more explanatory; can be several sentences or paragraphs. In literary analysis, identify which type is used AND analyze its specific effect: what does the comparison reveal, highlight, or distort about the thing being described?","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"What is synecdoche and metonymy? Give an example of each.","ex":"Think about part-for-whole vs. related-thing substitution.","a":"Synecdoche: part stands for the whole (or whole for part). 'All hands on deck' — hands represent sailors. 'Give us this day our daily bread' — bread represents all food/sustenance. Metonymy: closely associated thing substitutes for what it represents. 'The White House announced...' — the building represents the administration. 'The pen is mightier than the sword' — pen=writing/words; sword=military force. Both are figures of substitution: synecdoche uses part of the referent; metonymy uses something associated with it.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is an allusion and how do you analyze its function?","ex":"Think about intertextual reference.","a":"Allusion: a brief reference to a person, place, event, or text assumed to be known by the audience. Functions: (1) Compresses meaning — one reference can invoke an entire narrative or tradition; (2) Creates prestige or irony through association; (3) Positions the reader — knowing or not knowing the allusion creates in-groups; (4) Enriches interpretation — the alluded text's meanings layer onto the current text. Analysis: identify the allusion, explain the source, explain what associations are invoked, and analyze how those associations serve the current text's purposes.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is paradox in literature and how does it create meaning?","ex":"Think about apparent contradiction that reveals truth.","a":"Paradox: a statement that appears contradictory but reveals a deeper truth when examined. Examples: 'Less is more'; 'The more you give, the more you have'; 'Cowards die many times before their deaths' (Caesar). Functions: (1) Arrests attention — violation of logical expectation demands engagement; (2) Suggests reality exceeds logic; (3) Captures contradictions inherent in human experience; (4) Reveals that two apparently opposite things are true simultaneously. In analysis: state the apparent contradiction, then explain the deeper truth the paradox reveals about the work's theme.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is personification and how does it shape a reader's relationship to non-human subjects?","ex":"Think about attribution of human qualities.","a":"Personification: giving human attributes to non-human entities. Effects: (1) Creates intimacy or sympathy — we relate to what seems human; (2) Makes abstract forces tangible ('Death strode through the village'); (3) Can create irony by juxtaposing human characteristics with inhuman entities; (4) Often carries ideological content — personifying 'the market' as rational, or 'nature' as indifferent, shapes how readers understand these systems. Analysis: what human qualities are attributed? What does this attribution suggest about how the author understands the non-human entity?","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is dramatic monologue as a poetic form and what does it uniquely offer?","ex":"Think about Browning's poetry.","a":"Dramatic monologue: a poem in which a character (not the poet) speaks to a silent listener at a specific dramatic moment. Browning's 'My Last Duchess' is the paradigm. What it offers: (1) Gap between what the speaker says and what the reader perceives — irony through self-revelation; (2) Character study — the speaker reveals themselves through what they choose to say and how; (3) The silent listener's presence is implied and shapes the speech; (4) Reader becomes the listener — positioned critically. The form is ideal for psychological complexity and moral ambiguity.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is the pathetic fallacy and how is it used in literary texts?","ex":"Think about when nature mirrors human emotion.","a":"Pathetic fallacy (Ruskin's term): the attribution of human emotions or responses to nature or inanimate objects — the weather reflects the character's emotional state. Storm during grief; sunshine during joy. Functions: (1) Creates atmospheric unity (inner and outer worlds aligned); (2) Provides emotional cue for the reader; (3) When used ironically (gorgeous day during tragedy), creates powerful contrast; (4) Can suggest the universe is responsive to human experience — or that humans project onto an indifferent universe. Modern analysis often examines whether the pathetic fallacy is sincere or ironic.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How does diction function differently in poetry vs. prose?","ex":"Think about density, precision, and resonance.","a":"In poetry, diction bears far more weight: each word is chosen with extraordinary precision because density is higher (fewer words must do more work). Poetic diction: sound patterns (alliteration, assonance, consonance) are actively meaningful; connotation is primary; ambiguity is often productive; word placement within meter and line creates additional meaning. In prose, diction is less immediately conspicuous — it accumulates through pattern and repetition rather than single-word intensity. Both require asking: why this word? But poetry's compression means each word choice has proportionally greater impact.","diff":"hard"}
    ]},
    {"title":"Literary Argument Essay","problems":[
      {"q":"What is the difference between a literary analysis essay and a literary response?","ex":"Think about argument vs. reaction.","a":"Literary response: expressing how the text made you feel or what you personally took from it — subjective, impressionistic ('I found Hamlet relatable because...'). Literary analysis: making a specific, arguable claim about HOW and WHY the text creates meaning — supported by textual evidence and explained through literary reasoning. Analysis essays are not about your reactions — they're about the text's structure, choices, and effects. You use evidence from the text to support an argument that other careful readers could evaluate.","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"How do you construct a strong literary analysis thesis?","ex":"Think about what it must include.","a":"A strong literary thesis: (1) Names the text and author; (2) Makes a specific, arguable claim about the text's meaning or technique — not a plot summary; (3) Names the literary devices or strategies used; (4) Explains what effect or meaning those strategies create. Not strong: 'In Hamlet, Shakespeare explores themes of revenge and mortality.' Strong: 'In Hamlet, Shakespeare uses the play-within-a-play as a structural and thematic pivot — it exposes the gap between performance and truth that governs both the court's corruption and Hamlet's own paralysis, implicating theatre itself in the ethical dilemmas the play diagnoses.'","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is the difference between theme and thematic statement?","ex":"Think about topic vs. claim.","a":"Theme (as topic): a general subject or concern the text explores — love, mortality, power, identity. This is not arguable on its own. Thematic statement: a specific claim the text makes about that topic — 'Love is inseparable from destruction,' 'Power corrupts those who believe themselves virtuous,' 'Identity is performed rather than discovered.' A thematic statement can be true or false, supported or undermined. Literary analysis requires thematic statements, not just theme topics. When someone asks 'What is the theme?' they usually want a thematic statement.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"""How do you use quotation evidence effectively in a literary essay?""","ex":"""Think about selection, integration, and analysis.""","a":"""Effective quotation use: (1) Select the most precise, specific quotation for your claim — not the longest; (2) Integrate grammatically: 'When Hamlet declares that the world is "an unweeded garden," his disgust...' (3) Analyze immediately: explain what the quotation shows, how it shows it, and why it matters for your argument; (4) Use short quotations (phrase-level) rather than long block quotes when possible — they show control; (5) Never end a paragraph with a quotation — always follow with analysis. The quotation serves your argument; you don't serve the quotation.""","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is a 'lens essay' in literary analysis and how does it work?","ex":"Think about using one text to read another.","a":"Lens essay: using one text (the 'lens') to illuminate and analyze another (the 'object') — the lens provides concepts, frameworks, or questions that reveal something in the object text you'd miss without it. Example: use Freudian theory of repression to read Hamlet's procrastination; use Marx's concept of commodity fetishism to read Flaubert's descriptions of objects in Madame Bovary. The lens should genuinely illuminate — not be forced onto the text. The goal: the analysis through the lens reveals something true and specific about the object text.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"How do you analyze a novel's narrative arc in relation to its theme?","ex":"Think about structure and meaning.","a":"Narrative arc → theme: the shape of the plot enacts or argues the thematic position. A tragedy (rise → catastrophic fall) argues something about hubris, fate, or human limitation. A comedy (chaos → restoration of order) argues something about society's resilience. A novel without conventional resolution (The Trial) argues something about bureaucracy's irrationality or human powerlessness. Bildungsroman (development arc) argues something about how identity is formed. The narrative arc is not just what happens — it's an argument about how the world works. Identifying the arc type and asking what it claims is fundamental to thematic analysis.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is the purpose of the conclusion in a literary analysis essay?","ex":"Think about what comes after you've made your argument.","a":"The conclusion should: (1) Not merely restate the thesis and body points; (2) Synthesize — show how the parts of your analysis work together to create something larger; (3) Address broader implications: what does this analysis suggest about human experience, literary tradition, or the culture that produced the text? (4) Consider what remains — a work of genuine complexity won't be fully exhausted by your analysis; acknowledging what you haven't resolved demonstrates intellectual honesty; (5) End with resonance — a final sentence or image that leaves the reader with something to consider, not a bureaucratic summary.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you approach the AP Lit open-ended essay question (Q3)?","ex":"Think about how to choose a work and build an argument.","a":"Q3 approach: (1) Choose a work you know deeply — you need specific evidence; works of literary merit (canonical or serious contemporary fiction/drama/poetry); (2) Read the prompt very carefully — it names a specific literary element or concept; (3) Construct a thesis before you write — know your argument; (4) Select 3-4 pieces of textual evidence and know what you'll say about each; (5) Connect everything to the prompt's concept and to theme; (6) Don't just retell the plot — every sentence should be analytical; (7) Name specific characters, scenes, quotations (approximate if needed); (8) Strong conclusion that addresses the work's overall significance.","diff":"medium"}
    ]},
    {"title":"Free-Response Poetry Essay","problems":[
      {"q":"How do you approach an AP Lit poetry essay when the poem is unfamiliar?","ex":"Think about process, not just knowledge.","a":"Process: (1) Read the poem twice — first for tone and emotional register; second for structure and devices; (2) Annotate: mark shifts, significant images, figurative language, formal features; (3) Identify the speaker, situation, and occasion; (4) Identify the poem's central tension or question; (5) Read the prompt carefully — it usually names a concept to analyze; (6) Draft a thesis before writing; (7) Select evidence you can analyze specifically; (8) Write the essay making a clear argument, not just a tour of devices. Unknown poems require reading skill, not pre-knowledge.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you analyze a poem's speaker rather than conflating speaker with poet?","ex":"Think about who speaks, in what circumstances, to whom.","a":"Speaker analysis: (1) Who is speaking? (named character, anonymous 'I', collective 'we'); (2) What is the dramatic situation? (what is happening? to whom?); (3) What is the speaker's emotional state and how does it shift?; (4) Is the speaker reliable or self-deceived?; (5) Who is the speaker addressing? (a specific person, an absent figure, the reader, God); (6) What does the speaker want from the address?; (7) What does the speaker reveal about themselves that they might not intend to reveal? The speaker is always a construct — analyzing the construct illuminates the poem's meaning.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is a poem's occasion and why does it matter for interpretation?","ex":"Think about what prompted the poem.","a":"Occasion: the specific circumstance or event that prompted the poem — a death, a season, a moment of observation, a public event. Matters for interpretation because: (1) It explains what the poem responds to; (2) It establishes the emotional register appropriate to the moment; (3) It positions the speaker in time and space; (4) Occasionally, the occasion is ironic (a joyful occasion prompts a dark meditation — the gap creates meaning). In elegies, the occasion (grief) is inseparable from the poem's purpose. In lyrics, the occasion often anchors an abstract meditation.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you analyze the effect of a poem's rhyme scheme?","ex":"Think about end rhyme, internal rhyme, slant rhyme, and their effects.","a":"Full rhyme (perfect rhyme): creates closure, satisfaction, musical pleasure — or mechanical predictability if overdone. Slant rhyme (near rhyme): creates unease, incompleteness — consonance without full resolution (Dickinson's characteristic move). Internal rhyme: creates additional music within the line. Absent rhyme (free verse): focuses attention on other sound patterns (alliteration, assonance, consonance) or line breaks. A poem that abandons rhyme at a crucial moment: the absence is meaningful — creates surprise, resistance, incompletion. Always ask: does the rhyme scheme reinforce or resist the emotional content?","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What role does sound play in a poem's meaning beyond its literal content?","ex":"Think about onomatopoeia, alliteration, assonance, consonance.","a":"Sound as meaning: (1) Onomatopoeia — word sounds mimic their meaning ('crash,' 'murmur'); (2) Alliteration — repeated initial consonants create emphasis, unity, or difficulty (hard consonants: tension; soft: ease); (3) Assonance — repeated vowel sounds create tone (long vowels: openness, longing; short: sharpness, urgency); (4) Consonance — repeated consonant sounds in the body of words. The term 'music of poetry' is literal: sound creates emotional response independent of semantic content. Poe's 'The Bells' and Hopkins's 'The Windhover' are masterclasses in sound as meaning.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"How do you analyze the relationship between a poem's form and its argument?","ex":"Think about how the container shapes the content.","a":"Form-argument relationship examples: Sonnet (14 lines, volta): the form proposes a turn — use the volta to understand where the poem's argument pivots. Villanelle (two repeating refrains): the repetition is the argument — how do the repeated lines change meaning each time? Free verse: freedom of form may argue freedom of thought, or may build its own organic structure that mimics natural rhythms. Haiku: compression argues the significance of the fleeting moment. The question: does the poem embrace its form's conventions (reinforcing expected meanings) or work against them (creating productive tension)?","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is the difference between the AP Lit poetry essay (Q1) and the prose passage essay (Q2)?","ex":"Think about what each requires.","a":"Poetry essay (Q1): poem provided; analyze how the poet uses literary techniques to convey meaning — focus on poetic devices (meter, diction, imagery, tone, figurative language, structure, speaker). Prose essay (Q2): passage from fiction provided; analyze how literary techniques contribute to meaning — focus on narrative techniques (characterization, point of view, syntax, diction, detail, structure, figurative language). Both require: a thesis about HOW the text works and WHY, textual evidence, and literary analysis. Prose essays more often focus on character, narrator, and narrative strategy; poetry essays more often on speaker, sound, and formal features.","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"What is the scoring rubric for the AP Lit poetry essay?","ex":"Think about the three categories.","a":"AP Lit Free-Response Rubric (same for Q1, Q2, Q3): (1) Thesis (0-1 pt): defensible interpretation of how literary technique contributes to meaning — specific, not a restatement. (2) Evidence and Commentary (0-4 pts): 1=irrelevant/minimal; 2=evidence with limited commentary; 3=evidence with adequate commentary connecting to thesis; 4=consistently effective, specific evidence with insightful commentary. (3) Sophistication (0-1 pt): demonstrates complex literary understanding — nuance, tension, broader implications, particularly effective prose. Maximum: 6 points.","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"How do you end a poetry analysis essay effectively?","ex":"Think about what to synthesize and what to leave open.","a":"Effective poetry conclusion: (1) Don't restate body paragraphs; (2) Synthesize how the devices you analyzed work together to create the poem's overall effect; (3) Address the poem's significance — what does this poem claim about human experience that makes it worth reading?; (4) Consider what remains unresolved or unaddressed — a great poem resists total explanation; acknowledging its mystery shows sophistication; (5) End with a sentence that has rhetorical resonance — perhaps mirroring the poem's own ending, or stating the thematic insight cleanly. Avoid: 'In conclusion, this poem uses many literary devices effectively.'","diff":"medium"}
    ]},
    {"title":"Open Question Essay","problems":[
      {"q":"What works qualify for the AP Lit Q3 open question and what makes a work 'of literary merit'?","ex":"Think about what counts.","a":"Literary merit: works that use language in sophisticated, intentional ways to convey complex meaning — not genre fiction purely for entertainment (Dan Brown, Twilight), but serious literary fiction, drama, or epic poetry. Standard choices: Shakespeare, Fitzgerald, Morrison, Dostoevsky, García Márquez, O'Connor, Achebe, Camus, Chekhov, Austen, etc. Modern serious literary fiction is acceptable. You may also use works NOT on the suggested list — but they must meet the literary merit standard. Avoid: purely autobiographical accounts without literary craft, genre formula fiction, YA adventure series.","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"How do you match a literary work to an unfamiliar Q3 prompt?","ex":"Think about what the prompt is really asking.","a":"Strategy: (1) Identify the literary concept the prompt names (a character who chooses expediency over morality, a work where ambiguity functions as a theme, etc.); (2) Brainstorm works you know where this concept appears richly and specifically — not superficially; (3) Choose the work you can support with the most specific evidence; (4) Articulate how the concept functions in THAT work before you write; (5) If a work doesn't quite fit, don't force it — choose another. Many works can fit most prompts if you're creative — the key is finding specific evidence, not finding the 'perfect' work.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What does 'complexity' mean in the AP Lit Q3 essay?","ex":"Think about the sophistication point.","a":"Complexity in Q3: (1) Acknowledging a tension or ambiguity in the work you can't fully resolve ('While the novel appears to celebrate freedom, it simultaneously suggests that freedom without community is another form of prison'); (2) Connecting the specific to the universal — showing how the literary work's particular story illuminates broader human experience; (3) Engaging with the work's deliberate ambiguity; (4) Demonstrating that you understand the work resists simple thematic reduction; (5) Using particularly precise and controlled literary language. Complexity is not achieved by using the word 'complex.'","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"How many literary works should you know well for the AP Lit exam and how should you prepare them?","ex":"Think about breadth vs. depth.","a":"Recommendation: know 3-5 works DEEPLY rather than 10 works superficially. For each prepared work: (1) Know the plot thoroughly (specific scenes, characters, plot structure); (2) Memorize 3-5 quotations (approximate is fine — paraphrase if needed); (3) Know at least 3 literary devices or techniques the work uses distinctively; (4) Have 3-4 thematic claims you can make about the work with specific evidence; (5) Know the work's form/genre and how it shapes meaning. Breadth ensures you can find a match for any prompt; depth ensures you can argue specifically rather than vaguely.","diff":"easy"},
      {"q":"What is the difference between analyzing how a work means vs. what it means?","ex":"Think about craft vs. content.","a":"What it means: the thematic content — 'The novel is about the corruption of the American Dream.' How it means: the craft — 'Fitzgerald creates the illusion of glamour through Gatsby's sensory excess (the parties' vivid descriptions) and then systematically corrupts each image with decay (the faded sign, Gatsby's manufactured history) — so the reader experiences the seductiveness and the hollowness simultaneously rather than being told about it.' AP Lit rewards 'how' analysis because it engages with the author's craft. 'What' statements alone are insufficient — they stop where analysis should begin.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"How do you use a tragic work in a Q3 essay about hope or resilience?","ex":"Think about how you frame the work's evidence.","a":"Even tragic works contain moments or characters that embody what the prompt addresses — often ironically or aspirationally. In a tragedy, hope or resilience might function as: (1) What is lost (the tragedy measures what hopeful characters lose — which is itself about hope's value); (2) What minor characters represent against the protagonist's fall; (3) What the structure of the work argues (a tragedy that dignifies the hero's choices can be a statement about human dignity, a form of resilience). The key: you don't need to argue the work is optimistic — you need to argue how the concept the prompt names functions in this specific text, whatever its overall tone.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What are the most common mistakes in the Q3 open question essay?","ex":"Think about what loses points.","a":"Common Q3 mistakes: (1) Plot summary — describing what happens without analyzing how or why; (2) Vague evidence — 'In the novel, characters face hardship' without specifics; (3) Wrong work — choosing something without enough complexity (memoir, YA genre fiction); (4) Not addressing the prompt — arguing a thesis that doesn't engage the specific concept asked; (5) Underdeveloped analysis — making claims without explaining HOW the literary choices create the claimed effect; (6) No thesis — beginning with 'In this essay I will discuss...'; (7) Weak conclusion that summarizes rather than synthesizes.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you construct a Q3 essay about a complex character?","ex":"Think about what makes a character 'complex.'","a":"Character complexity essay: (1) Thesis: claim about HOW the character's complexity functions in the work's larger meaning (not just 'X is complex'); (2) Identify the specific contradictions or tensions within the character; (3) Show HOW the author renders this complexity — through specific scenes, dialogue, narrative perspective; (4) Explain why this complexity is thematically significant — what does it argue about human nature, society, or the human condition?; (5) Consider whether the character achieves self-knowledge and what the work implies about self-knowledge's value. Complexity means internal contradiction, not just 'having many traits.'","diff":"hard"}
    ]},
    {"title":"Thematic Analysis Across Major Works","problems":[
      {"q":"What is the difference between a motif and a theme?","ex":"Think about recurring element vs. central claim.","a":"Motif: a recurring element (image, symbol, phrase, situation) that appears throughout a work — water in a work about purification and drowning; a window in a work about constraint and freedom; a recurring phrase. Motifs are building blocks of theme. Theme: the central claim or insight about human experience that the work as a whole conveys. A motif of mirrors might contribute to a theme about self-delusion and identity. Motifs are identifiable textual elements; themes are the interpretive claims built from those elements and from the work's overall argument.","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"How do you trace the development of a theme across a long work?","ex":"Think about how themes evolve and complicate.","a":"Thematic development: (1) Identify early statement of theme — often it's introduced simply; (2) Track how each subsequent event or character complicates, extends, or challenges it; (3) Note the moment of maximum tension — when the theme is most contested; (4) Analyze the resolution or lack thereof — does the work affirm, qualify, or undermine the early thematic statement? A sophisticated work rarely ends where it began. The ending's relationship to the opening thematic statement is itself an argument. Map the journey as an arc of developing understanding.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"How does literature from a specific historical period reflect the concerns of that period without being reducible to it?","ex":"Think about context and universality.","a":"Literature is both of its moment and beyond it. Historical grounding: a text's specific concerns, assumptions, anxieties, and blindnesses reflect the culture and moment that produced it — you can't fully understand Invisible Man without knowing postwar America, or Beloved without Reconstruction and slavery's aftermath. Beyond its moment: what makes great literature endure is its articulation of something that persists — about grief, power, identity, human dignity — that continues to resonate. Analysis should acknowledge both dimensions: how the text is historically specific AND what it illuminates that transcends its moment.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"How do you compare and contrast two literary works thematically?","ex":"Think about what to compare and how to structure it.","a":"Comparison strategy: (1) Establish a clear basis of comparison — a specific thematic concept both works address; (2) Don't alternate (A then B then A then B) — instead, focus each paragraph on the concept and show how each work handles it; (3) Look for agreement, disagreement, and unexpected similarity (two very different works might converge on a shared insight); (4) Analyze how each work's formal choices (genre, structure, style) affect its thematic treatment; (5) Reach a synthesizing conclusion — what does comparing the two reveal that examining either alone would miss?","diff":"medium"},
      {"q":"What is the 'anxiety of influence' (Harold Bloom) and how does it illuminate literary tradition?","ex":"Think about how later writers relate to predecessors.","a":"Anxiety of influence (Bloom, 1973): major poets/writers are always in a fraught relationship with their literary predecessors — they admire them, are shaped by them, but must 'misread' or 'revise' them to create space for their own originality. A strong poem is always a response to a precursor poem, whether acknowledged or not. Illuminates: why writers revisit the same stories (every retelling of Hamlet, Antigone, Medea is a new argument); how tradition constrains and enables; why originality is always in tension with inheritance. In literary analysis: recognizing what a text revises clarifies its specific argument.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"How does gender function as a literary theme and what analytical approaches help illuminate it?","ex":"Think about how gender shapes character and narrative.","a":"Gender in literary analysis: (1) How are gendered expectations constructed and enforced within the narrative world?; (2) Whose interiority is granted access — whose perspective is centered?; (3) What happens when characters transgress gender expectations (as punishment, liberation, tragedy)?; (4) What does the narrative reward and punish?; (5) How does genre itself encode gender (the marriage plot, the male Bildungsroman)?. Feminist literary criticism examines these questions. Applying it: look at who speaks and who is spoken about; who acts and who is acted upon; what futures are available to characters of different genders.","diff":"hard"},
      {"q":"What is postcolonial literary criticism and how does it illuminate texts from or about colonized peoples?","ex":"Think about power, voice, and representation.","a":"Postcolonial criticism (Said, Spivak, Bhabha): examines how colonialism and its legacy are represented in literature — who speaks, who is spoken for, how power relations structure narrative. Key questions: (1) Whose story is told and from whose perspective?; (2) How are colonized peoples represented by colonial writers (as Other, exotic, savage)?; (3) How do writers from colonized cultures reclaim narrative voice (Achebe, Ngugi, Rushdie)?; (4) What is cultural hybridity and ambivalence?; (5) How does language itself carry colonial power? Things Fall Apart directly answers Heart of Darkness — both are illuminated by reading them in this dialogue.","diff":"hard"}
    ]}
  ]
]
